	<div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<h6 class="kicker"></h6>
<div class="ru-story">
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/04/morning-agenda-calling-for-an-apology-cease-fire/" data-title="Hold the Apologies" data-description="The &quot;Apology Watch&quot; begins on the DealBook website. | A crowded courtroom heard closing arguments in the insider trading trial of a former SAC manager. | In Detroit bankruptcy, it is Wall Street vs. Main Street. | Stocks slumped Monday on disappointing economic data.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWhat does saying âsorryâ mean when itâs tossed around with the frequency of a <b>Justin Bieber scandal?â</b> <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/03/too-many-sorry-excuses-for-apology">asks Andrew Ross Sorkin in the DealBook column.</a></b> Almost every day, some prominent figure â a chief executive, a politician, an athlete â is apologizing for something â to say nothing of the average person. Are we in the midst of <b>an apology crisis?</b> To hear <b>Dov Seidman</b> talk about it, the answer is an emphatic yes. And in fact, Mr. Seidman is so sure that <b>our mea culpas have become meaningless</b> that he called for an <b>âapology cease-fireâ</b> in front of several dozen chief executives and politicians at the World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ââSorryâ is in a sorry state,â <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/03/calling-for-an-apology-cease-fire">Mr. Seidman writes in an essay.</a></b> âThe transparent âget me out of this messâ declarations we are witnessing are bereft of credibility. They are motivated by strategic plotting, not soul-searching.â For an apology to mean something, five essential characteristics must be met and internalized, which Mr. Seidman lays out in his essay.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Beginning on Tuesday, <b>Mr. Sorkin and Mr. Seidman are starting âApology Watchâ</b> on the DealBook website (<a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/">nytimes.com/dealbook</a>). And this is where you, our readers, come in. Help us track new apologies and, more important, follow up on what companies, institutions and individuals have done post-apology, by <b>leaving a comment on the website</b> and on <b>Twitter using the hashtag <a href="https://www.twitter.com/search?q=%23apologywatch">#ApologyWatch.</a></b></p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">CLOSING ARGUMENTS IN FORMER SAC MANAGERâS TRIAL DRAW A CROWD <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Everyone, it seems, wanted to hear the closing arguments on Monday in the insider trading trial against Mathew Martoma, a former portfolio manager at SAC Capital Advisors. The courtroom was packed, with nearly two dozen spectators forced to stand against the wall, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/03/closing-arguments-in-martoma-trial">Alexandra Stevenson writes in DealBook. </a></b></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The prosecutor said Mr. Martoma pursued a <b>âcanary in a coal mineâ</b> to give him an <b>âillegal sneak previewâ</b> of the results of a clinical Alzheimerâs drug trial. To find this canary, the prosecutor said, Mr. Martoma fostered relationships with two doctors involved in the drug trial, giving him an inside look at the trialâs negative results before they were announced publicly. This advance knowledge allowed SAC to avoid losses and make profits totaling $275 million, the prosecutor said. The defense countered by saying that the <b>governmentâs case against Mr. Martoma was âfatally flawedâ</b> and hinged on a <b>doctor with a faulty memory.</b> The jury is expected to begin <b>deliberating on Tuesday.</b></p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">IN DETROIT, ITâS âUS VERSUS THEMâ <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Detroitâs bankruptcy has unnerved the cityâs creditors, to say nothing of how it has affected the cityâs everyday denizens. Now, it seems, the cityâs bankruptcy is turning into a <b>battle of Wall Street versus Main Street</b>, at least in the eyes of these creditors, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/03/detroit-turns-bankruptcy-into-challenge-of-banks">Mary Williams Walsh writes in DealBook.</a></b> And to bondholders, bond insurers and other financial institutions, this clash only grew worse last week, when the city circulated plans to emerge from bankruptcy and filed a lawsuit on Friday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the lawsuit, which seeks to nullify complex financial contracts that once helped finance Detroitâs pension system, the city said the deal was done <b>âat the prompting of investment banks that would profit handsomely from the transaction.â</b> As for the cityâs plan to resolve its bankruptcy, banks, bond insurers and other corporate creditors think they are being asked to share a disproportionate amount of pain under the plan. Under the plan, pensioners would receive up to 50 cents on the dollar for their claims, while unsecured creditors, like general-obligation municipal bondholders, would only end up with 20 cents on the dollar.</p>
</div>
